commit.message:
60-io-scheduler.rules: no scheduler for multipath components

multipath components should use no IO scheduler, to avoid allocating
possibly huge amounts of unreclaimable memory for unused blk-mq
requests (bsc#1192161).

In order to treat multipath components right, we need to act on
change events. The restriction to "add" events dates back to 2014
fc5362d2ef ("udev: use 'deadline' IO scheduler for SSD disks"),
and https://bugzilla.suse.com/show_bug.cgi?id=904517#c25.

The rationale given there was "CHANGE events happen a lot of times, especially
when creating/removing partitions". This is a minor performance-related
aspect; handling multipath correctly is more important.

What we can do instead to avoid accessing sysfs pointlessly is acting on disks
only. Partitions don't even have the scheduler attribute.

60-io-scheduler.rules: add copyright notice and fix comments

... make it clear that editing should happen in the bottom part only.

60-io-scheduler.rules: only use bfq for single-queue HDDs by default

The kernel defaults to "none" for devices with more than one hctx.
Keep this default. Using an IO scheduler for such devices may require
a large amount of unreclaimable memory (bsc#1192161).

60-io-scheduler.rules: add comment

This comment was requested for the version pushed to SLE15-SP3
in the systemd package.

commit.message:
60-io-scheduler.rules: add comments and sample rules

The only current default rule is to use BFQ for rotational devices.
Add some other alternative rules as examples for users who want
to change the rules.

60-io-scheduler.rules: drop code for legacy IO path

Since kernel v5.0, only blk-mq needs to be supported. Neither is the
"elevator" kernel parameter. Simplify the rules accordingly.

60-io-scheduler.rules: skip zoned devices

The kernel auto-configures schedulers for zoned devices based
on the scheduler features logic. Let's not override that.

60-io-scheduler-rules: skip non-configurable devices

Devices for which the "scheduler" attribute shows simply "none"
are not request based (not blk-mq based in newer kernels). Don't
attempt to configure an IO scheduler for them.

60-io-scheduler.rules: fix logic for dm devices

For dm devices, we need to check change events, not add events.

commit.message:
Do not automagically online memory on s390x (bsc#1127557).

On s390 memory that is not online is typically 'reserve' memory that
should be only activated by the system administrator.

There is no way to detect reserve memory from information provided by
the kernel so the state of the art is to not activate memory
automagically if the platform is s390.

Signed-off-by: Michal Suchanek <msuchanek@suse.de>

commit.message:
systemd: ignore the exit code of systemd-detect-virt for memory hot-add

In 80-hotplug-cpu-mem.rules on SLE12-SP3, there have a memory hot-add rule
uses systemd-detect-virt to detect non-zvm environment. The
systemd-detect-virt returns exit failure code when it detected _none_ state.
The exit failure code causes that the hot-add memory block can not be set to
online.

This patch follows Franck Bui's suggestion on sytstemd upstream to
ignore exit code:
        https://www.spinics.net/lists/systemd-devel/msg00341.html
